metadata.name: Elegant Reality #8
metadata.description:
"Elegant Reality" is a Generative-Art that consists of an infinite number of different variations. Each mint is presented in high quality (3200x3200 px) so that it can be printed in case you want to print it.
The design process focused on the color harmony and uniformity of the work, and during a time-consuming process, in addition to being unique, each work was shown to represent harmony and elegance.
Reality always has a certain elegance, every part of the structure of a reality, like the world around us, plays an irreplaceable role, which, if removed from that seemingly small part, disrupts harmony. This work of art is made up of millions of small dots, each component of which plays an important role in showing harmony and integrity.

It can take up to 30-40 seconds to produce each artwork, as it is created from millions of points.
Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.
To see the full high-quality image, I suggest you open it in a new tab or just directly open it in live mode.

metadata.name: Conspiracy Theory #49
metadata.description:
The idea is inspired by the conspiracy board.

Conspiracy theories may go so far that even people, in newspapers and books, look for clues. 
The text is from Alice in Wonderland, which is randomly selected and then words are selected to be highlighted and circled, and eventually numbers may be written next to some of them to create a network of clues.

Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.
Made with P5js.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #330
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: A creative tunnel that leads to nothing #32
metadata.description:
This piece is dedicated to all those forgotten projects that have been left behind, maybe they were just simple ideas that didn't stick, or maybe full blown complex creations, never completed, never released...just stuff on the walls of a tunnel that ends into nothing.

Goodbye.

Time to move on.

#tezosartweek

metadata.name: Liquid mirror #101
Haemo Globs #394
metadata.description:
The shape and function of haematids (red blood cells) has always fascinated me. Perhaps their mathematical smoothness and candy-like aspect resonated with me as a child. Their simple appearance distinguished them from the other cell types I had learned about. I imagined them engorged with sweet-flavoured oxygen and juicily popping under my bite.

I hope for this generative artwork to communicate my appreciation for these never-ending body travellers.

metadata.name: Ambiguous Instances #46
metadata.description:
“Ambiguous Instances” is the sixth collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

Often people use a specific example to argue their point of view. Unfortunately, this means that they can completely make it up or hyperbolise it to benefit their views, which means that it's a completely invalid argument.

Statistics, on the other hand, cannot lie, since they are just pure observations.
That is unless they are completely made up, of course.

metadata.name: The Face We Had #123
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: Elswhere #199
metadata.description:
Perlin noise walks into a Julia set and finds itself Elswhere. X is real, Y is imaginary, or is it the other way around? 

Elswhere is a unique generative art series in which noise and fractal math are combined to create whimsical shapes and motifs, with an infinite number of variations. Made with p5js.

For each pixel, the noise values corresponding to the X and Y coordinates are computed and then used as the real and imaginary components for initializing a Julia set recursion. The pixel is colored based on the number of steps it takes for the recursion to reach its base case.

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view.
[2] Render 2000x3000px image.
[4] Render 4000x6000px image.
[6] Render 6000x9000px image.

Created by Elsif, 2022.05

metadata.name: Mitosis #18
metadata.description:
Mitosis is a part of the cell cycle in which replicated chromosomes are separated into two new nuclei. Cell division gives rise to genetically identical cells in which the total number of chromosomes is maintained.

Every piece is animated, but animation is slow, be patient.

metadata.description:
We meander through the flows of life, alone but together. This experience — an ultimately solitary one — is communicated but never truly shared. Our consciousnesses live in a perpetual separated state, alone but together.

metadata.name: THE400FLIPS #228
metadata.description:
The more they flip. The more you’ll make.

p5.js –> Blockchain


Controls:

[s] save as PNG.
[a] render alternate higher resolution artwork (takes a few seconds).
[z] save alternate artwork as PNG.


Artist note:

Primary royalties are split 95-5% between artist and The Processing Foundation.

Secondary royalties go to the minters (99.9% of the 15%).

The preview thumbnails don’t do justice to the artworks. Please run the code to appreciate them better. Also, remember to check the alternate higher resolution renders using [a].

Some preview thumbnails might look slightly different to the artwork seen when running the code. This is due to the resolution difference between the capture module and the live code on your device. 

Please get in touch in the event of a blank preview thumbnail. 

Made in p5.js and rendered in webGL. Tested on Chrome and Safari.
